article.description:
Allison Feaster scored five of her 14 points in overtime, lifting
the Sting to a 63-58 win over the Sun on Friday night.
article.headline: Feaster scores OT tiebreaker
article.linkText: Feaster, Sting extinguish the Sun in OT
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- It didn't matter that Allison Feaster
missed seven straight shots. The next two she made counted the
most.

Feaster connected on consecutive baskets in overtime -- a
3-pointer and a 16-foot jumper -- to lift the Charlotte Sting to a
63-58 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Friday night.

"I didn't feel good in the first part of the game," Feaster
said. "But I have to credit my teammates. They kept talking to me
and encouraging me."

She got the message.

Feaster scored five of her team-high 14 points in overtime. Her
3-pointer gave the Sting a 57-55 lead with 2:04 left. After Taj
McWilliams-Franklin tied it for Connecticut with a layup, Feaster
popped off a screen and drained a 16-footer to break the tie and
put Charlotte up to stay.

"That's the sign of a great shooter," Sting coach Trudi Lacey
said. "Allison knows that when she is open, she has the freedom to
take that. We keep telling her to shoot the ball with confidence."

After Feaster's go-ahead jumper, the Sting made 4 of 6 shots
from the foul line to ice their third straight win.

Connecticut dropped its second straight game in overtime and is
0-4 in OT since the franchise moved from Orlando last year. Nykesha
Sales scored all 19 of her points for the Sun in the second half.

Tammy Sutton-Brown anchored a dominating post for Charlotte and
finished with 11 rebounds and 10 points. She was in foul trouble
for most of the second half but managed to come up with key
defensive rebounds late.

The Sting finished with a 40-30 rebounding edge. Charlotte
Taylor-Smith added 10.

Sutton-Brown got Charlotte out to an early lead, opening the
game with two quick inside baskets. Charlotte outrebounded
Connecticut 21-13 in the first half and led by four points at
halftime.

"We wanted to come out early and focus on getting the ball to
Tammy Sutton-Brown," Taylor-Smith said. "She did a great job of
executing offensively."

Sales, 0-for-4 in the first half, took over for Connecticut in
the second -- scoring the Sun's first 15 points. Her three-point
play with 11:33 left in regulation tied it at 37.

Jennifer Derevjanik gave Connecticut its first lead of the half
with a driving layup with 8:49 left, kicking off a 9-4 run that
gave the Sun their biggest lead, 49-44.

Charlotte rookie Nicole Powell countered with a 3-pointer, and
the Sting came back over the next three minutes to take a 51-49
lead with 6.2 seconds left in regulation. Sales missed a layup on
Connecticut's next possession, but Taj McWilliams-Franklin got the
putback with 0.4 seconds left to send the game into overtime.

The Sun had just returned from a four-game road trip to the West
Coast and came out sluggish in the first half, missing several
wide-open layups.

"We really didn't take bad shots. It's just that when we get
them, they don't go in," Sales said. "We didn't make the
chippies."
